2020-04-02T08:25:40: An Essex modified Flat V Crump weir situated in a mainly rural headwaters with urban influences.
'Essex' (modified Flat V Crump) weir in 10.4m wide section. The weir is non-standard. Spillway accommodates flow > 16 cumecs.
Model-based calibration assumes modularity and drowning is uncommon. Rating estimates of flow thought to be reasonable. One peak flow rating has been applied across the period of record.
Naturalised flows available 1966-7, there is a very small net diminution in runoff. The site was vandalised and data was lost between 01/07/00 and 28/01/01.
A predominantly impermeable catchment (London Clay overlain in places by glacial deposits). Mainly rural headwaters with substantial expanding urban development in the lower reaches.
Runoff increased by effluent returns but reduced by industrial/agricultural abstraction. Flood storage lagoons built on the River Rom, from the late 1980s onwards, influences flows patterns.
